In his 2013 State of the Union Address, President Obama said, “A growing 
economy that creates good, middle class jobs, that must be the North Star 
that guides our efforts.”  But the slow growth, and negligible job creation 
under Obama, in turn have caused steeply declining middle class incomes.  
The latest numbers compiled from the Census Bureau’s Current Population 
Survey show that real median household income declined by more than $4,500 
during Obama’s first term, about 8%, meaning effectively that the middle 
class has lost annually the equivalent of one month’s pay under Obama.  
Even President Bush again did better during his disastrous second term, 
when real median household income at least rose by 1.7%, not enough, but 
still positive rather than negative.
Even if you start from when the recession ended in June, 2009, the decline 
in median real household income since then has been greater than it was 
during the recession.  Four years into the supposed Obama recovery, real 
median household income has declined nearly 6% as compared to June, 2009.  
That is more than twice the decline of 2.6% that occurred during the 
recession from December, 2007 until June, 2009.  As the Wall Street Journal 
summarized in its August 25-26, 2012 weekend edition, “For household 
income, in other words, the Obama recovery has been worse than the Bush 
recession.”Despite his rhetoric, Obama has failed to deliver for the poor 
as well.  But we know Obama loves the poor, because he has created so many 
of them.  Indeed, the only thing booming under Obamanomics has been 
poverty.  Poverty has soared under Obama, with the number of Americans in 
poverty increasing to the highest level in the more than 50 years that the 
Census Bureau has been tracking poverty.  Over the last 5 years, the number 
in poverty has increased by nearly 31%, to 49.7 million, with the poverty 
rate climbing by over 30% to 16.1%.  This is another natural result of 
negligible economic growth, paltry job creation, declining real wages, and 
the worst economic recovery since the Great Depression!﻿

United States Constitution: Article II Sections 2 and 3;  (for those who 
don't know these sections outline the powers and duties of the president.)

Section. 2. 

The President shall be Commander in Chief of the Army and Navy of the 
United States, and of the Militia of the several States, when called into 
the actual Service of the United States; he may require the Opinion, in 
writing, of the principal Officer in each of the executive Departments, 
upon any Subject relating to the Duties of their respective Offices, and he 
shall have Power to grant Reprieves and Pardons for Offences against the 
United States, except in Cases of Impeachment.

He shall have Power, by and with the Advice and Consent of the Senate, to 
make Treaties, provided two thirds of the Senators present concur; and he 
shall nominate, and by and with the Advice and Consent of the Senate, shall 
appoint Ambassadors, other public Ministers and Consuls, Judges of the 
supreme Court, and all other Officers of the United States, whose 
Appointments are not herein otherwise provided for, and which shall be 
established by Law: but the Congress may by Law vest the Appointment of 
such inferior Officers, as they think proper, in the President alone, in 
the Courts of Law, or in the Heads of Departments.

The President shall have Power to fill up all Vacancies that may happen 
during the Recess of the Senate, by granting Commissions which shall expire 
at the End of their next Session.

Section. 3.

He shall from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of 
the Union, and recommend to their Consideration such Measures as he shall 
judge necessary and expedient; he may, on extraordinary Occasions, convene 
both Houses, or either of them, and in Case of Disagreement between them, 
with Respect to the Time of Adjournment, he may adjourn them to such Time 
as he shall think proper; he shall receive Ambassadors and other public 
Ministers; he shall take Care that the Laws be faithfully executed, and 
shall Commission all the Officers of the United States.

Do you think corporations have too much influence over our government?

It is never a good idea to give a few so much power over the rest. The 
power to dictate what happens in a private transaction like pay is a 
slippery slope. When was the last time politicians looked to remove laws 
from the books? Never, because laws equal control. I don't know about you 
but I will take my chances on myself. I don't need empty promises from 
politicians who never help anyone but themselves.

+MISTERORANGE NONE I don't work for most of them any longer, however, each 
new employer turns out to be the same.. Thus my frustration with "Corporate 
America".

I don't think finding a better job is the solution. Not for everyone. It 
would only help me, or some people, but not most. Because these 
corporations are "running the show". The real problem is changing how they 
run their business, not trying to circumvent them by becoming self 
employed, or "somehow" creating a sustainable better business, that can 
compete with corporations.

Also keep in mind that you're trying to infer a lot from my personal 
situation, which I have not divulged all the details of. Nor will I take 
the time to describe every detail and answer every question surrounding my 
employment. Lol. It's beside the point..

This is not my personal issue, but the issue of most people working for 
these corporations at close to minimum wage. As for what is so "terrible" 
about these jobs, there are some examples I could give, but the one that 
everyone could relate to is the lack of full time hours/pay. They hire you 
as "full time", then give you a notice describing that their corporate 
definition of full time is actually part-time. Around 32 hours/week. Lol. 
Because they will NOT pay overtime, or full time benefits. 

And the only reason all of this exists, is because Capitalism allows it. We 
need more Socialist economic reforms. More business cooperatives, that 
manage business more fairly, and place the power in the hands of the 
workers. "Social ownership" of the economy is the way to go, not giving it 
to corporations, whose only goal is to accumulate capital for themselves.

So why do you aspire to work for companies you believe have bad business 
practices and are idiotic?

The fact you don't have a better choice IS the problem. Your NOT supposed 
to stay there, you are supposed to move on to better employment, or 
business ownership, especially when you feel you could run things better. 

You need to want to move on to a better job as you learn the basics. You 
can't stay a Walmart your whole life and bitch about the wages and work 
conditions. (Although I don't understand what working conditions could be 
so horrible at Walmart after working two summers pouring concrete in the 
desert. )

+MISTERORANGE NONE I don't see an inherent problem with forcing employers 
to comply with the Fair Minimum Wage Act. It even has the word "fair" in it 
to better emphasize its purpose. I don't care if employers don't like 
"being told how to run their business", IF they are not treating employees 
FAIRLY.

If you find my idea of "livable" to be atrocious, hopefully you see my 
point. Which is, even that can't be supported by minimum wage, for most 
people. So there's just no reason for the min. wage to be that low anymore.

Sears and Wal Mart invest a lot of time in training new employees and have

future, because like other poorly run businesses, they just make the 
MANAGERS do the extra work. So when employees get promoted to managing

comes to hourly employment. Salaried employment is a whole other thing, and 
generally has much better relations between employee and employer.

The jobs that pay close to minimum wage, are generally terrible jobs 
already. It's like adding insult to injury. And nothing will change an 
employer's attitude about how much they should pay employees for those 
positions. Certainly not the opportunity for better jobs in the area, 
because they're counting on hiring people who can't get those jobs. Like 
people with criminal backgrounds, who are illegal immigrants, bad work 
history, etc. They'll always find someone willing to do the work, if only 
for a short time. Thus, high turnover, shitty pay, terrible working 
conditions persist.

And that's what the Fair Minimum Wage Act can rectify. To prevent 
employers, especially corporations, from exploiting people who can't get a 
better job. And if a corporation is going to take the time to spend hours 
and days describing the history of their business to new employees, having 
them take tests and orientation/safety videos, it just makes sense to pay 
them a fair wage. Since obviously they're investing a lot into them (it

No, the Treasury is an "executive department" meaning that the President, 
the leader of the executive branch of the U.S. government, has direct 
authority over it. It's a common misconception that the president controls 
the budget through the Treasury, though. What happens is the president will 
send a budget to Congress who will introduce their own draft--frequently, 
they add their own batter into the proverbial cake mix. Congress will then 
send a bill the president. It's been many years since the budget Congress 
sends the president has been budget neutral. The president is obligated to 
fulfill the requirements of the budget that Congress adopts, which means he 
has to direct the Treasury to issue bonds and other debt that finances that 
extra bit Congress couldn't fund but wanted in the bill anyways.

Washington (AFP) - US President Barack Obama on Tuesday was to urge 
lawmakers to endow him with new war powers to defeat Islamic State 
militants, warning the battle would be long but eventually successful.
"This effort will take time. It will require focus. But we will succeed," 
Obama was to say, according to excerpts of his State of the Union address 
released by the White House.
"In Iraq and Syria, American leadership -– including our military power -– 
is stopping ISIL's advance," the commander-in-chief was to tell US 
lawmakers.
"Instead of getting dragged into another ground war in the Middle East, we 
are leading a broad coalition, including Arab nations, to degrade and 
ultimately destroy this terrorist group," Obama was to say.
"We're also supporting a moderate opposition in Syria that can help us in 
this effort, and assisting people everywhere who stand up to the bankrupt 
ideology of violent extremism."
But in order to emerge victorious, Obama will appeal to gathered lawmakers 
to give him a new authorization to use military force against the Islamic 
State group, also known as ISIL, which has seized a swathe of territory in 
Iraq and Syria.
The US has already unleashed dozens of airstrikes against the militants 
since September, using the powers enshrined in legislation adopted in the 
wake of the September 2001 attacks to hunt down Al-Qaeda and its affiliates.
But US officials have argued that a new Authorization for Use of Military 
Force (AUMF) is needed.
"Tonight, I call on this Congress to show the world that we are united in 
this mission by passing a resolution to authorize the use of force against 
ISIL," Obama was to say.

The definition of socialism is a political and economic theory of social 
organization that advocates that the means of production, distribution, and 
exchange should be owned or regulated by the community as a whole. 
Democracy and socialism go hand in hand. When done well a democratic 
government is run by the people as a whole for the people as a whole, when 
a socialist government is run as it is meant to be run, it is for the 
people as a whole and by the people as a whole, while I understand that 
many fear socialism, You must put into perspective the fears of democracy, 
as well. Democracy does the "tango" with corruption day in and day out, 
especially in our modern world. There are too many ways for those who have 
the most influence in our country to get away with corruption for their own 
political agenda. Both parties are guilty of this. While a purely socialist 
government would never work in this country, leaning towards the ideology 
of what socialism is meant to do for its citizens is not a bad thing for a 
democratic government. In fact, it is encouraged. When we live in a world 
and country that is so divided because of social and/or economic class, we 
need some parts of the socialist ideology, so that we can get back on track 
to how our country was supposed to be run. The definition of democracy is a 
system of government by the whole population or all the eligible members of 
a state, typically through elected representatives. Which means our elected 
representatives advocate for what we want as the people of this country but 
when our "elected" leaders fall short of this responsibility, and when we 
as the people are losing our voice for what the government and our elected 
leaders should be doing, a more socialist way of going about things can be 
necessary for sustaining our rights as American citizens. I wouldn't call 
Obama a socialist, but I would call him freedom, and equality orientated, 
as should be all of our congressional and senate leaders. We as a country 
are more focused on Republican or Democrat, when we should be focused on 
the well-being of our citizens as a whole, we should be directing our 
efforts into what’s best for everybody, not just what’s best for me as an 
individual. But that seems to be the mentality in our country currently. We 
are so stuck on being right, or being the majority leaders in the HoR, that 
they seem to forget why they are there to begin with. Our country was not 
built on the hierarchy system of Medieval Europe, and when it feels like we 
have reverted back to the 12th and 13th century, there are some changes 
that should be in order. The evolution of government is inevitable with the 
daunting rise of the technological era, and due to this fact we should be 
implementing our own ideals for what works today not reverting back to what 
worked yesterday. The world is changing every day, and we have to keep up. 
And by restlessly arguing over issues that should be morally simple to 
figure out, we instead debate and debate, and shut down the government, and 
go on recess, instead of compromising with those who disagree with us. For 
them it’s simpler to disagree than to try finding common ground. We seem to 
forget that this country was literally built off of the compromises made 
between the two political parties of the 1700's. It is sad to think that 
the people who started this country were more mature than the ones who 
define it today, and that the vision of our democracy and the vision of a 
bipartisan government by the people and for the people are slowly shrinking 
into the distance. Everyday our citizens become more and more infuriated 
with those who are running our government, on both sides of the political 
field. It is not only hard to watch but put simply...ridiculous. What does 
this all mean it means what should be happening and what is happening are 
not always one and the same, and that they should be! Your own political 
agenda becomes irrelevant if it does not do what’s best for the people of 
this country. We are ONE country, not TWO parties. It is time to act like 
it.
